{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"879145a1-633f-40dd-a611-199b3f34fc45","content":"For a .NET Web API project, use the `webapi` template:\n\n```bash\ndotnet new webapi -n MyApi\n```\n\n**Authentication options** (via `--auth`):\n\n| Option | Description |\n|---|---|\n| `None` | No auth (default) |\n| `IndividualB2C` | Azure AD B2C individual accounts |\n| `SingleOrg` | Single-tenant Azure AD |\n| `MultiOrg` | Multi-tenant Azure AD |\n| `Windows` | Windows authentication |\n\n**Examples:**\n\n```bash\n# Azure AD single-org auth\ndotnet new webapi --auth SingleOrg --domain yourdomain.com --tenant-id <id> --client-id <id>\n\n# Azure AD B2C\ndotnet new webapi --auth IndividualB2C\n```\n\nYou can also add JWT Bearer auth manually via `Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authentication.JwtBearer` if you need a custom identity provider. Run `dotnet new webapi --help` for all options.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3f3f670d-f351-4842-a38e-04a86a9607f3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about web API project templates and authentication options. This is a general knowledge question about .NET (likely, given the repository context with dotnet plugins). I can answer this from my knowledge without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":307,"requestId":"1C39:551B:AEA37F9:BD46078:69FD3372"},"id":"340cfc4d-49a0-4c40-a947-7706be37745f","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:51:05.250Z","parentId":"ea4e3a14-81b0-4cf7-8042-19634ad4bd33"}
